1	0	'ab	awb	a primitive word; father, in a literal and immediate, or figurative and remote application):--chief, (fore-)father(-less),    patrimony, principal. Compare names in "Abi-".
1	1	a	al'-fah	of Hebrew origin; the first letter of the alphabet; figuratively, only (from its use as a numeral) the first: --Alpha. Often used (usually an, before a vowel) also in composition (as a contraction from 427) in the sense of privation; so, in many words, beginning with this letter; occasionally in the sense of union (as a contraction of 260).
2	0	'ab	ab	(Aramaic) corresponding to 1:--father.
2	1	Aaron	ah-ar-ohn'	of Hebrew origin (175); Aaron, the brother of Moses:--Aaron.
3	0	'eb	abe	from the same as 24; a green plant:--greenness, fruit.

4	0	'eb	abe	(Aramaic) corresponding to 3:--fruit.
4	1	abares	ab-ar-ace'	from 1 (as a negative particle) and 922; weightless, i.e. (figuratively) not burdensome:--from being burdensome.
5	0	'Abagtha'	ab-ag-thaw'	of foreign origin; Abagtha, a eunuch of  erxes:--Abagtha.
5	1	Abba	ab-bah'	of Chaldee origin (2); father as a vocative:--Abba.
6	0	'abad	aw-bad'	a primitive root; properly, to wander away, i.e. lose oneself; by implication to perish (causative, destroy):--break, destroy(- uction),   not escape, fail, lose, (cause to, make) perish, spend,    and surely, take, be undone,    utterly, be void of, have no way to flee.
